article.description: Chantelle Anderson scored a game-high 24 points as No. 17 Vanderbilt defeated No. 4 Louisiana State 72-60 Sunday.
article.headline: Anderson leads the way in second half
article.linkText: Nothing's for sure: Vandy upsets No. 4 LSU
article.story:
NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Vanderbilt seems to know just how to
beat LSU.

	   Chantelle Anderson scored a game-high 24 points as No. 17
Vanderbilt (No. 18 ESPN/USA Today, No. 17 AP) beat No. 4 LSU 72-60 on Sunday.

	   Vanderbilt (19-8, 9-5) has now won seven of the last eight
meetings between the two teams, including last year's Southeastern
Conference tournament championship game avenged a 70-59 loss in
Baton Rouge on Jan. 26.

	   The Commodores' lone loss in that stretch was 70-59 on Jan. 26
in Baton Rouge.

	   Junior forwards Jenni Benningfield and Hillary Hager teamed for
26 points and 20 rebounds, as Benningfield notched her 10th
double-double of the season with 17 points and 11 rebounds on
senior night.

	   "Our coaches wanted everybody to be ready to play for them,''
Benningfield said, regarding the postgame festivities to recognize
Anderson and Ashley McElhiney. "I wanted to give something back to
them because they've given me so much over my three years.''

	   Vanderbilt took a 20-12 lead in the first half. But the
Commodores scored just two points in a span of seven minutes and
allowed LSU to take a 24-22 advantage on a three-point play by
Aiysha Smith, who finished with 12 points and 10 rebounds for her
fourth double-double of the year.

	   "I felt we had a lull offensively,'' Vanderbilt coach Melanie
Balcomb said. "We weren't executing. Even when we had good shots,
we weren't hitting them. But we turned up our defense. The defense
stepped up and created opportunities. That really helped us.''

	   Vanderbilt regrouped to take a 30-28 lead at halftime, and LSU
(24-3, 11-3) never led in the second half. Vanderbilt went ahead
70-57 with 1:02 remaining on a pair of free throws by McElhiney,
who did not play in the earlier loss because of a sprained ankle.

	   "Vanderbilt set the tone early, and we didn't respond to it,''
LSU coach Sue Gunter said. "It meant something to them. They
played really well. They had an answer and they made plays; we
didn't have an answer and we didn't make plays.''

	   Doneeka Hodges scored 14 points to lead four double-digit
scorers for LSU. Temeka Johnson and Seimone Augustus each scored
12.
